./.summary: Learn what makes Go the best language for cloud.
./.body:
About

Go is an open source programming language that make it easy to build simple, reliable and efficient software.
Only through simplicity of design can a sistem remain stable, secure and coherent as it grows.

Requirements

install golang
install code editor, I use Goland
will to assimilate new information 

Why I like go

made by Rob Pike, Ken Thomson, Robert Griesemer
it's made for cloud. Try to achieve maximum effect with minimum mean
clean syntax
compiled language
static types
garbage collection
package system
backward compatibility: go programs can be compiled and run with newer versions of compilers and standard libraries.
concurrent and parallel programming language
amazing standard libraries

Comparison with other technologies
Go is very good at developing web servers. Has a built in standard library with great performance and security.

The speed execution of instruction is very fast. Go is one of the fastest language with Garbage Collector.

basics/first-go-program.html.title: First Go Program
basics/first-go-program.html.summary: Learn how to write, run and read the source code.
basics/first-go-program.html.body:
How to write a Go program

Create directory inside GoPath: mkdir -p src/github.com/name
Create file hello.go with the content:

package main

import "fmt"

// this is a comment
func main() {
    fmt.Println("Hello, World")
}


Run go run main.go and the output on terminal is: $ Hello World

How to read a Go program

the program is readed from top to bottom, left to right
package main is the package declaration. There are two types of go programs: executables and libraries. Every executable - program - needs a package main. 
Libraries are a way of reusing code and for convention they get the same package name as the folder.
the white line has no meaning for the compiler. They are usefull only to make the code more readable.
import fmt is how we include code from other packages.
// represents a comment. This is usefull for make the code more readable and for go to generate documentation.
func main() {} is a function that represents the execution point of the program. Every executable should have a main() function.
fmt.Println("Hello, World") is the syntax to access a function Println() from the package fmt.
The function tekes one string argument Hello World and prints with new line the string to the terminal.

Find more information
Type into the terminal: godoc fmt Println

syntax/structure.html.title: Structure
syntax/structure.html.summary: Generic overview about naming the code, files, keywords, scope
syntax/structure.html.body:
Names
Part of code that is written is composed by custom names for variables, functions, ecc.
The names need to begin with a letter or undescore and can have any number of additional letters, undescores, digits.
The names should be camel case, should be short for local scope and more meaningfull and longer for larger scope.
Keywords
Go has 25 keywords:
break, default, func, interface, select, case, defer, go, map, struct, chan, else, goto, package, switch, const, fallthrough, if, range, type, continue, for, import, var, return
Scope
Is a part of code at wich a declared name refers to.
...

func f() {}

var g = "g"

func main() {
    f := "f"
    fmt.Println(f) // "f"; local var f shadows package-level func f
    fmt.Println(g) // "g"; package-level var
    fmt.Println(h) // compile error: undefined: h
}

There are four types of declarations: var, cons, type, func.
Structure
A Go program is stored in one or more files that end in .go. Each file begin with package that says what package the file is part of. 
After package there is an import declaration and then a sequace of package level declarations.

syntax/variables.html.title: Variables
syntax/variables.html.summary: Learn how an information is saved into mamory.
syntax/variables.html.body:
Variables
A var declaration creates a variable of a particular type with a name and set its initial value.
var val int
fmt.Println(val) // 0

In this case the val variable is created and initialized to it's zero value.
The zero value for types are: 0 for numbers, false for booleans, "" for strings and nil for interfaces or reference types (slice, pointer, map, chanel, function)
How a variable is saved into memory?

We write the code:

var val int


We execute: go run main.go or go build
Compiler checks for errors
Compiler checks its symbol table to see if val has been already defined into the program.



Compiler created a definition for val.

 

Now val is declared. It exist in the system table but not have an lvalue (location into memory of pc)
Compiler send message to system Memory Management to ask if the pc has free space for an int variable. The System Memory Management decide that the int can be saved starting from address 625 in memory.



Now val is defined; it has an lvalue into system memory.
If val is used now it will be initialized to it's zero value. This is done by Go automatically to prevent errors like using the informations that could be present into memory.

Assignment
var val = 10
var val int = 10 // the same
val := 10 // short syntax available only inside functions


The value 10 is stored at the location in memory 625.


package main

import "fmt"

func addOne(v *int) {  
    *v++ // like *v = *v + 1
         // with * we get the rvalue of address
}

func main() {
    val := 10

    fmt.Println(&val) // hex: 0xc420014050
                      // base10: 17716822096
                      // bin: 00000000000000000000000000000100001000000000000100000001010000



    fmt.Println(val) // 10

    fmt.Println(addOne(&val)) // 11

    _ := 20
}


& is used to get the lvalue of variable and the output is in hex. In the case above the variable lives in memory at lvalue: 0xc420014050. The Memory Management decide where to put the variable into memory.
* is used to indicate that the variable, in the example above, v is a pointer to an int. The variable contains a memory address.
* is used to get the rvalue of the type to be able to modify the data (dereference the value).

syntax/data-types.html.body:
Golang Data Types
The information, in a computer, is stored into capacitors and transistor as electric impulses.
Lower impulse than 0.8V represent a zero and a higher impulse, up to 5V, represent an one.
The zero and one, in programming, are called bits.
Computers operate on fixed sized bits (numbers) called words.
Words can be interpreted as integers, floating point numbers, bit sets or memory address that can be combined into larger 
aggregated that represent pixels, books, ecc.
Go offers four ways to orgagnise data:

basic types: numbers (integers, floating point numbers, complex numbers), booleans, strings
aggregate types: arrays and structs
reference types: slices, maps, functions, pointers, channels
interface type

Go binary operators
Go binaries operators for logic, comparison and arithmetic can be applied on types and are: 
* / % > & &^ +-|^
== !=  >=
&&
||
The operators are in decreasing order.
Numbers range sizes



Data type
Range
Range Unsigned




int8
-128 to 127
0 to 256


int16
-32768 to 32767
0 to 65535


int32
-2147483648 to 2147483647
0 to 4294967295


int64
-9223372036854775808 to 9223372036854775807
0 to 18446744073709551615


float32
1.4e-45 to 3.4e38
-

1.8e308 to 4.9e-324

Overflow
Overflow in Golang is safe.
var u uint8 = 255
fmt.Println(u, u+1, u*u) // "255 0 1"
var i int8 = 127
fmt.Println(i, i+1, i*i) // "127 -128 1"

syntax/basic-data-types.html.title: Basic data types
syntax/basic-data-types.html.summary: Learn about Go basic data types like strings, numbers and booleans
syntax/basic-data-types.html.body:
Basic Data Types
Integers
There are five sizes if integers:

int8, int16, int32, int64, int with corresponding unsigned versions uint8, uint16, uint32, uint64, uint.
The int data type depend on the architecture of the computer and is assigned automatically by the compiler.

There are also two synonyms:

rune that is synonym of int32 and indicates that the value is a Unicode code point.
byte that is synonym of int8 and indicates that the value is a pice of raw code.

Finally there is uintptr that can hold the bits of any pointer value.
var money int = 0

Floating Point Numbers
Go provides two sizes of floating point numbers: float32 and floaat64.
A float32 provides a six decimal digits precision. The float64 provides almost 15 digits.
var f float = 1.2

Booleans
Booleans has only two possible values: true and false.
Boolean values can be combined with the && (AND) and || (OR) operators, which have short-circuit behavior : if the answer is already determined by the value of the left operand, the right operand is not evaluated, making it safe to write expressions like this:
s != "" && s[0] == 'x'

where s[0] would panic if applied to an empty string.
Strings
A string is an immutable sequence of bytes.
Text strings are conventionally interpreted as UTF-8-encoded sequences of Unicode code points (runes).
s := "hello, world"     // "hello world" represent a string literal
fmt.Println(len(s))     // "12"
fmt.Println(s[0], s[7]) // "104 119"  ('h' and 'w')

Since strings are immutable and constructors like this are invalid:
s[0] = 'L' // compile error: cannot assign to s[0]

Immutability means that it is safe for two copies of string to share the same underlying memory, making it cheap to copy strings of any length.
Similarly, a string s and a substring s[7:] may safely share the same data; no new memory is allocated in either case.
String literals
"Hello World" represent a string literal.
Inside double quoted string literal can be inserted ASCII control lines:
\a alert or bell
\b backspace
\f form feed
\n new line
\r carrige return
\t tab
\v vertical tab
\' single quote (only inside rune literal '\'')
\" double quote (only within " " literals)

Arbitrary bytes can also be included in literal strings using hexadecimal or octal escapes.
Raw literals
A raw string literal is written ..., using backquotes instead of double quotes. Within a raw string literal, no escape sequences are processed; the contents are taken literally, including backslashes and newlines, so a raw string literal may spread over several lines in the program source. 
UTF-8
Go source files are always encoded in UTF-8, and UTF-8 is the preferred encoding for text strings manipulated by Go programs.
There are two form of unicode: \uhhhh for a 16-bit value and \Uhhhhhhhh for a 32-bit value, where each h is a hexadecimal digit
Usefull packages
Four standard packages are particularly important for manipulating strings: bytes, strings, strconv, and unicode. 
The strings package provides many functions for searching, replacing, comparing, trimming, splitting, and joining strings.
The bytes package has similar functions for manipulating slices of bytes, of type []byte, which share some properties with strings. Because strings are immutable, building up strings incrementally can involve a lot of allocation and copying . In such cases, itâ€™s more efficient to use the bytes.
func intsToString(values []int) string {
    var buf bytes.Buffer
    buf.WriteByte('[')
    for i, v := range values {
        if i > 0 {
            buf.WriteString(", ")
        }
        fmt.Fprintf(&buf, "%d", v)
    }
    buf.WriteByte(']')
    return buf.String()
}

func main() {
    fmt.Println(intsToString([]int{1, 2, 3})) // "[1, 2, 3]"
}

The strconv package provides functions for converting boolean, integer, and floating-point values to and from their string representations, and functions for quoting and unquoting strings.
The unicode package provides functions like IsDigit, IsLetter, IsUpper, and IsLower for classifying runes. Each function takes a single rune argument and returns a boolean. Conversion functions like ToUpper and ToLower convert a rune into the given case if it is a letter. All these functions use the Unicode standard categories for letters, digits, and so on. The strings package has similar functions, also called ToUpper and ToLower, that return a new string with the specified transformation applied to each character of the original string.  
Constants
Constants are expressions whose values are known at compile time. Constants are made by basic types: booleans, strings or numbers.
const pi = 3.14159 // approximately; math.Pi is a better approximation

To create enumerators, in Go, can be used the iota keyword.
type Weekday int

const (
    Sunday Weekday = iota
    Monday
    Tuesday
    Wednesday
    Thursday
    Friday
    Saturday
)

This declares Sunday to be 0, Monday to be 1, and so on.

syntax/aggregate-data-types.html.title: Aggregate data types
syntax/aggregate-data-types.html.summary: Learn about Go aggregate data types like Array and Structs
syntax/aggregate-data-types.html.body:
Aggregate Data Types
Arrays
An array is a numbered sequence of elements of a single type with a fixed length. In Go, they look like this:
var x [5]int

var x [5]int
x[4] = 100     // set the fifth element of an array to 100
fmt.Println(x)

var x [5]float64
x[0] = 98
x[1] = 93
x[2] = 77
x[3] = 82
x[4] = 83

x := [5]float64{ 98, 93, 77, 82, 83 } // short notation
x := [...]float64{ 98, 93, 77, 82, 83 } // the ... creates automatically the index

Structs
A struct is a type that contains named fields.
type Circle struct {
    x float64
    y float64
    r float64
}

var c Circle          // initialize struct with fields set to their default value
c := new(Circle)      // like above but return pointer and allocate memory for all fields
c := Circle{x: 0, y: 0, r: 5} // more readable syntax
c := Circle{0, 0, 5}  // the same as above
c := &Circle{0, 0, 5} // alternative to new keyword

Fields of Struct
Fields can be access with the . operator.
A structâ€™s fields usually represent the has-a relationship (e.g., a Circle has a radius).
fmt.Println(c.x, c.y, c.r) 
c.x=10
c.y=5

Methods
Methods are a special type of function.
func (c *Circle) area() float64 { 
    return math.Pi * c.r*c.r
}

fmt.Println(c.area())

For more informations on methods see OOP section.
Embedded Types
The embedded type represent the is-a relationship.
For example, in the code below, the Android is a person.
The embedded type is Person and Android can access Person methods.
type Person struct { 
    Name string
}
func (p *Person) Talk() { 
    fmt.Println("Hi, my name is", p.Name)
}

type Android struct { 
    Person 
    Model string 
}

a := new(Android)
a.Person.Talk()
a.Talk() // the same as above

syntax/reference-data-types.html.title: Reference data types
syntax/reference-data-types.html.summary: Learn about Go reference data types like slices, maps, functions, channels and pointers.
syntax/reference-data-types.html.body:
Reference Data Types
Slices
A slice is a segment of an array. Like arrays slices are indexable and have a length that is allowed to change.
var x []float64             // x has length zero and we can not insert value into x
x := make([]float64, 5)     // x is associated with an underlying array of len 5
x := make([]float64, 5, 10) // x has a length of 5 but hte underlying array has capacity 10

append
slice1 := []int{1,2,3}
slice2 := append(slice1, 4, 5)

The result of slice2 is [1 2 3 4 5]
copy
slice1 := []int{1,2,3} 
slice2 := make([]int, 2)
copy(slice2, slice1)

The copy function will copy slice1 into slice2. Because slice2 has a length of 2, only 1 and 2 will be copy.
Maps
Maps is an unordered collection of key value-pairs.
var x map[string]int

x is a map of string keys and integers values. but if we try to initialize the map with values we get an error:
x["key"] = 10
fmt.Println(x) // panic: runtime error: assignment to entry in nil map

The error is because the map points to a nil value. The map has no underlying structure.
To fix the error we use the make function.
x := make(map[string]int) 
x["key"] = 10
fmt.Println(x["key"]) // 10

delete
delete(x, "key") // this will delete the key field from map

Examples
elements := make(map[string]string)
    elements["H"] = "Hydrogen"
    elements["He"] = "Helium"
    elements["Li"] = "Lithium"
    elements["Be"] = "Beryllium"
    elements["B"] = "Boron"
    elements["C"] = "Carbon"
    elements["N"] = "Nitrogen"
    elements["O"] = "Oxygen"
    elements["F"] = "Fluorine"
    elements["Ne"] = "Neon"
    fmt.Println(elements["Li"])
}

// shorter syntax
elements := map[string]string{"H": "Hydrogen",
    "He": "Helium",
    "Li": "Lithium",
    "Be": "Beryllium",
    "B": "Boron",
    "C": "Carbon",
    "N": "Nitrogen",
    "O": "Oxygen",
    "F": "Fluorine",
    "Ne": "Neon",
}

elements := map[string]map[string]string{
        "H": map[string]string{
            "name":  "Hydrogen",
            "state": "gas",
        },
        "He": map[string]string{
            "name":  "Helium",
            "state": "gas",
        },
        "Li": map[string]string{
            "name": "Lithium",
            "state": "solid",
        },
        "Be": map[string]string{
            "name":  "Beryllium",
            "state": "solid",
        },
        "B": map[string]string{
            "name": "Boron",
            "state": "solid",
        },
        "C": map[string]string{
            "name": "Carbon",
            "state": "solid",
        },
        "N": map[string]string{
            "name":  "Nitrogen",
            "state": "gas",
        },
        "O": map[string]string{
            "name": "Oxygen",
            "state": "gas",
        },
        "F": map[string]string{
            "name": "Fluorine",
            "state": "gas",
        },
        "Ne": map[string]string{
            "name":  "Neon",
            "state": "gas",
        },
    }
    if el, ok := elements["Li"]; ok {
        fmt.Println(el["name"], el["state"])
    }

In the last example the map stores as value another map.
The if statment is used to check if element Li is part of map.

syntax/concurrency.html.body:
Goroutine

Concurrency is about dealing with lots of things at once. Parallelism is about doing lots of things at once.

In Go each concurrently executed activity is called goroutine.
A goroutine is created using go keyword in front of a function.
The go keyword allows to launch a function that executes independently from it's calling function.
go keyword can be used on an existing function, an independent function or an expression that calls a function.
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

var wg sync.WaitGroup

func f(n int) {
    defer wg.Done()
    for i := 0; i 
output is:
1 : 0
1 : 1
1 : 2
1 : 3
2 : 0
2 : 1
0 : 0
0 : 1
0 : 2
0 : 3
2 : 2
2 : 3

As the output shows the f functions are executed concurrently.
wg is used to wait for all the concurrently function to complete. Without wg the main() will terminate before the concurrent function can finish.

In most cases the goroutine will see the last value. We can easily avoid this by passing the variable as a parameter in the function literal for the goroutine.
Channels
Channels are a mechanism of communication between two goroutines. Go uses the  operator to indicate movement of data.

There are two type of channels: buffered and unbuffered channels.

The channel is unbuffered because has no length and at every c  send the program will block until
fmt.Println( is executed. 
Characteristics:

If the channel is empty, the receiver blocks until there is data
The sender can send only to an empty channel and blocks until the next receive operation
When the channel has data, the receiver can proceed to receive the data.

buffered channels
package main

import (
    "fmt"

var counter int64

}

func f(n int) {

In the code above, the make() function is used to create an unbuffered chanel with a capacity
of 100. The buffered channel operates as a first-in-first-out blocking queue.
Characteristics:

When the channel is empty, the receiver blocks until there is at least one element
The sender always succeeds as long as the channel is not at capacity
When the channel is at capacity, the sender blocks until at least one element is received

close channel
close in the previous example is used to close the channel and stop the for range loop.

Subsequent send operations will cause a program to panic
Receive operations never block (regardless of whether buffered or unbuffered)

syntax/testing.html.summary: Learn how to write tests in Go
syntax/testing.html.body:
Testing
Writing tests for our code is a good way to ensure quality and improve reliability.
Inside math folder from packages create a math_test.go file with the content:
package math

import "testing"

func TestAverage(t *testing.T) {
    v := Average([]float64{1, 2})
    if v != 1.5 {
        t.Error("Expected 1.5, got ", v)
    }
}

go test and the result should be PASS
Commands for testing
go test // test all functions
go test . // like go test
go test -run=TestAverage // tests only the function specified
go test -v // result is verbose
go test -cover // show how much of actual code is getting tested

// Output test result to file
go test -coverprofile=cover.out // save to file cover.out the test result
go tool cover -func=cover.out   // pretty output of the contents of file
go tool cover -html=cover.out   // show result as HTML

syntax/benchmark.html.body:
Benchmarking
Benchmarking is a way of testing the performance of code. 
it's useful to test different solutions to the same problem.
func Add(a, b float64) float64 {
     return a + b
}

func Sub(a, b float64) float64 {
    return a - b
}

To test the performance of the above functions we use the testing file or if not created create an new one with the content:
func BenchmarkAdd(b *testing.B) {

Running the benchmark
go test -bench=.
